@name    Factory Dynamics
@author  N.N.
@version 1.0
@theme   light

# ============================================================
# Factory Production and Distribution Model
# Based on: Forrester, J.W. (1961). Industrial Dynamics. MIT Press.
#
# This model demonstrates the Bullwhip Effect: how small changes
# in customer demand amplify into large oscillations in production,
# inventory, and workforce throughout the supply chain.
#
# v1.2 — Structural corrections from deep logic review
#
#   1. effective_capacity auxiliary introduced.
#      workforce and production_capacity both constrain production
#      without either stock directly filling the other. The two-
#      integrator chain is preserved: both slow stocks accumulate
#      independently on their own timescales and feed production
#      jointly. This is the structural basis of bullwhip amplitude.
#
#   2. desired_workforce auxiliary introduced.
#      hire and fire are now two separate flows governed by a
#      goal-gap structure. This correctly models both workforce
#      expansion and workforce reduction — the second half of
#      the bullwhip cycle. A single unidirectional hire_fire
#      flow cannot produce overshoot-and-correct behaviour.
#
#   3. order_filling declared as an auxiliary (not a flow).
#      sale (draining inventory) and shipment (clearing backlog)
#      are co-flows governed by this single rate variable.
#      One physical event — delivering a unit to a customer —
#      must drain both stocks at exactly the same rate.
#
#   4. B5 (operational pressure loop) named and added to summary.
#      delivery_delay driving desired_workforce is a structurally
#      distinct balancing loop, independent of B4. Leaving it
#      unnamed obscures the compound-overshoot mechanism.
#
#   5. R1 reframed as a structural note, not a feedback loop.
#      No true positive loop exists in the connector graph.
#      The bullwhip arises from two slow balancing loops (B4, B5)
#      with independent inertia feeding a shared output node
#      (effective_capacity), not from positive self-reinforcement.
#
#   6. All stale comments and internal contradictions removed.
#
# ── Feedback loop summary ────────────────────────────────────
#
#  B1  Inventory-price balance (balancing)
#      inventory -(-) price -(-) orders -(+)-> backlog
#      -(+)-> order_filling -(+)-> sale -(-) inventory
#      Low inventory raises price; high price dampens demand.
#
#  B2  Customer delivery delay balance (balancing, with delay)
#      backlog -(+)-> delivery_delay -(-) orders -(+)-> backlog
#      Long customer wait times discourage new orders.
#      The delay in this loop produces oscillation in isolation.
#
#  B3  Capacity investment loop (balancing, slow)
#      price -(+)-> machine_orders -(+)-> machine_backlog
#      -(+)-> machine_delivery -(+)-> production_capacity
#      -(+)-> effective_capacity -(+)-> production
#      -(+)-> inventory -(-) price
#      High price triggers machine investment. New capacity
#      eventually fills inventory and brings price down.
#      Slowest loop; dominant source of long-period swings.
#
#  B4  Machine delivery delay compensation (balancing)
#      machine_backlog -(+)-> machine_delivery_delay
#      -(+)-> desired_workforce -(+)-> hire -(+)-> workforce
#      -(+)-> effective_capacity -(+)-> production
#      -(+)-> inventory -(-) price -(-) machine_orders
#      -(-) machine_backlog
#      Parallel fast closure via capacity:
#      machine_backlog -(+)-> machine_delivery
#      -(+)-> production_capacity -(-) desired_workforce
#      -(-) hire; fire -(-)-> workforce
#      While machines are on order the factory hires to bridge
#      the gap. When machines arrive production_capacity rises,
#      desired_workforce falls, and the fire rate exceeds the
#      hire rate — workforce contracts. Both halves of the cycle
#      are structurally present.
#
#  B5  Operational pressure loop (balancing, with delay)
#      backlog -(+)-> delivery_delay -(+)-> desired_workforce
#      -(+)-> hire -(+)-> workforce -(+)-> effective_capacity
#      -(+)-> production -(+)-> inventory -(+)-> order_filling
#      -(+)-> shipment -(-) backlog
#      Customer backlog directly pressures hiring, independent
#      of the machine delivery cycle (B4). Their combined and
#      unsynchronised overshoot is the primary mechanism that
#      amplifies oscillation beyond either loop alone.
#
#  Note on oscillation amplitude (structural, not a loop):
#      workforce and production_capacity are two independent slow
#      stocks, both feeding effective_capacity, both driven by
#      delayed negative feedback (B4, B5). Neither stock can
#      adjust instantaneously; their compound inertia means that
#      corrective action continues long after the error that
#      triggered it has passed. This is the structural origin of
#      the Bullwhip Effect — not a positive feedback loop, but
#      two slow integrators sharing an output node and driven by
#      signals that arrive with different lags.
#
# ============================================================


# ── Stocks (accumulators) ─────────────────────────────────────
#
# Stocks are the memory of the system. They cannot change
# instantaneously — only flows can alter them over time.
# This inertia is what creates delay and oscillation.

# Central warehouse stock. Filled by production, depleted by sale.
# Key junction between supply-side and demand-side dynamics.
stock inventory

# Unfulfilled customer orders awaiting delivery.
# Rises as orders arrive, falls as shipments are made.
# Drives customer delivery delay (B2) and operational hiring (B5).
stock backlog

# Installed production capacity — machines and infrastructure.
# Grows as machine deliveries arrive.
# One of two independent slow stocks feeding effective_capacity.
stock production_capacity

# Workforce level. Slowest-adjusting stock: hiring, onboarding
# and training take months; redundancy takes time too.
# Second independent slow stock feeding effective_capacity.
stock workforce

# Machines on order but not yet delivered.
# Orders accumulate here and drain into production_capacity
# as machines arrive. The lag between order and arrival is
# machine_delivery_delay — the core delay in loops B3 and B4.
stock machine_backlog


# ── Clouds (model boundaries) ────────────────────────────────
#
# Clouds are model boundaries: inexhaustible sources or
# absorbing sinks whose internal dynamics are not modelled.

cloud production_source  [source]  # Raw materials / inputs to production
cloud sales_sink         [sink]    # Goods sold leave the system here
cloud orders_source      [source]  # New customer orders enter here
cloud delivery_sink      [sink]    # Fulfilled orders leave the model boundary
cloud machine_capital    [source]  # Capital market — funds machine purchases
cloud labor_pool         [source]  # Labour market — workers available for hire


# ── Flows (rates) ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Flows are the only mechanism by which stocks change.
# Each valve (⊗) is where causal feedback from connectors acts.

# Rate at which finished goods enter inventory.
# Governed by effective_capacity and price signals (B1, B3).
flow production_source -> inventory : production (+) strong

# Rate at which inventory is consumed by customer deliveries.
# Governed by the order_filling auxiliary — same physical event
# as shipment. Both must drain at exactly the same rate.
flow inventory -> sales_sink : sale (-) medium

# Rate at which new customer orders accumulate in backlog.
# Sensitive to price (B1) and expected delivery delay (B2).
flow orders_source -> backlog : orders (+) medium

# Rate at which the customer backlog is cleared through shipments.
# Governed by the order_filling auxiliary — same physical event
# as sale. Both must drain at exactly the same rate.
flow backlog -> delivery_sink : shipment (-) medium

# Rate at which new machine orders are placed with suppliers.
# Driven by price signals and current capacity adequacy (B3).
# Flows into machine_backlog, not directly to production_capacity.
flow machine_capital -> machine_backlog : machine_orders (+) weak

# Rate at which ordered machines are delivered and installed.
# Drains machine_backlog; fills production_capacity.
# The lag between machine_orders and machine_delivery is
# machine_delivery_delay — core delay in loops B3 and B4.
flow machine_backlog -> production_capacity : machine_delivery (+) weak

# Hiring flow: draws workers from the labour pool.
# Active when desired_workforce exceeds current workforce.
# Rate governed by the gap (desired_workforce - workforce).
flow labor_pool -> workforce : hire (+) weak

# Firing flow: returns surplus workers to the labour pool.
# Active when current workforce exceeds desired_workforce.
# Rate governed by the gap (workforce - desired_workforce).
# This flow is essential: without it the model cannot reproduce
# the second half of the bullwhip cycle — the over-correction.
flow workforce -> labor_pool : fire (-) weak


# ── Auxiliary variables ───────────────────────────────────────
#
# Auxiliaries carry information, not material. They translate
# stock levels into signals that drive flow rates.

# Market price. Rises when inventory is scarce, falls when abundant.
# Central signal variable linking inventory to ordering (B1)
# and capital investment (B3).
aux price <- inventory (-)

# Customer-facing delivery lead time, derived from backlog level.
# When this rises, customers reduce new orders (B2) and
# operational hiring pressure increases (B5).
aux delivery_delay <- backlog (+)

# Factory-facing delivery lead time for capital equipment.
# Derived from machine_backlog level.
# When machines are slow to arrive, hiring is triggered to
# compensate for the missing mechanical capacity (B4).
# When machines finally arrive and production_capacity rises,
# desired_workforce falls and firing begins.
aux machine_delivery_delay <- machine_backlog (+)

# Binding production constraint — the lesser of machine capacity
# and labour-constrained throughput. If either is insufficient,
# the actual production rate is limited accordingly.
# Structurally critical: both slow stocks (production_capacity,
# workforce) feed production here without either conflating into
# the other. The two-integrator chain is fully preserved.
aux effective_capacity <- production_capacity (+)
connector effective_capacity <- workforce (+)

# Target workforce level, synthesised from operational signals.
# Rises when delivery or machine delivery delays indicate under-
# capacity; falls when production_capacity is already adequate.
# Governs both the hire and fire flows via a goal-gap structure:
#   hire rate ∝ max(0,  desired_workforce − workforce)
#   fire rate ∝ max(0,  workforce − desired_workforce)
aux desired_workforce <- delivery_delay (+)
connector desired_workforce <- machine_delivery_delay (+)
connector desired_workforce <- production_capacity (-)

# Unified order-fulfilment rate.
# One physical transaction — delivering a unit — simultaneously
# removes stock from inventory (sale) and removes the entry from
# backlog (shipment). Both flows are governed by this single rate.
# Inventory availability sets an upper bound; backlog urgency sets
# the operational pressure. Neither alone is sufficient.
aux order_filling <- inventory (+)
connector order_filling <- backlog (+)


# ── Causal connectors ─────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Connectors carry information between elements.
# (+) source and target move in the same direction.
# (-) source and target move in opposite directions.

# B1 — Inventory-price balance
connector orders         <- price (-)               # High price dampens customer demand B1
connector machine_orders <- price (+)               # High price makes investment attractive B3

# B2 — Customer delivery delay balance
connector orders <- delivery_delay (-)              # Long wait discourages new orders B2

# B3 — Capacity investment loop
connector production     <- effective_capacity (+)  # Effective capacity governs production rate
connector production     <- price (+)               # Price signal drives short-run output push
connector machine_orders <- production_capacity (-) # Adequate installed capacity dampens orders

# B4 — Machine delivery delay compensation
# desired_workforce auxiliary carries the signal; hire/fire flows act on the gap.
connector hire <- desired_workforce (+)             # Desired > actual → hire rate rises
connector hire <- workforce (-)                     # Gap closes as workforce accumulates
connector fire <- workforce (+)                     # Actual > desired → fire rate rises
connector fire <- desired_workforce (-)             # High desired reduces firing pressure
connector machine_delivery <- machine_backlog (+)   # Backlog size drives delivery rate B3, B4

# B5 — Operational pressure (delivery_delay → desired_workforce in aux definition above)

# Order fulfilment co-flows — one rate governs both stocks
connector sale     <- order_filling (+)             # Inventory drain equals order_filling rate
connector shipment <- order_filling (+)             # Backlog drain equals order_filling rate

@position inventory 267 510
@position backlog 975 258
@position production_capacity 1461 842
@position workforce 1007 762
@position machine_backlog 1204 210
@position production_source 251 258
@position sales_sink 482 252
@position orders_source 1081 377
@position delivery_sink 622 264
@position machine_capital 1511 85
@position labor_pool 660 737
@position price 506 595
@position delivery_delay 516 490
@position machine_delivery_delay 115 199
@position effective_capacity 699 402
@position desired_workforce 378 744
@position order_filling 622 127
